<subsection xml:id="subsec-representing-linear-inequalities-graphically" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Representing Linear Inequalities Graphically</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In many real-life situations, we deal with inequalities such as limits, budgets, or boundaries. Graphing these inequalities helps us visualize all the possible solutions that satisfy the conditions.
    </p>
    <p>
      When a linear inequality involves two variables (like <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>), its solution is a region in the coordinate plane, not just a line.
    </p>
    <p>
      The boundary line helps define where the inequality changes from true to false. We use:
      <ul>
        <li>Solid lines for inequalities like <m>\le</m> or <m>\ge</m></li>
        <li>Dashed lines for inequalities like <m>\lt</m> or <m>\gt</m></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-graphing-inequalities-one-variable">
    <title>Graphing Inequalities in One Variable</title>

    <activity>
      <p><m>\textbf{Try This in Pairs}</m></p>
      <p><term>What you need:</term></p>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>Graph paper</li>
          <li>Pencil and ruler</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p><m>\textbf{Instructions}</m></p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>Draw a number line on your graph paper.</li>
          <li>Solve and plot the inequality <m>x \ge -2</m>.</li>
          <li>Use a solid circle for <m>-2</m> and shade to the right.</li>
          <li>Now try <m>x \lt 3 </m> using a hollow circle at <m>3</m> and shade left.</li>
          <li>Discuss: What does overlapping of shaded areas mean?</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graph the inequality <m>x \le 1</m> on a number line.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Draw a number line with values from <m>-5</m> to <m>5</m>. Put a solid circle at <m>1</m> and shade everything to the left.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-graphing-two-variable">
    <title>Graphing Inequalities in Two Variables</title>

    <activity>
      <p><m>\textbf{Group Activity: Drawing Solution Regions}</m></p>
      <p><term>Materials:</term></p>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>Graph paper</li>
          <li>Coloured pencils</li>
          <li>Ruler</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p><m>\textbf{Instructions}</m></p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>Draw the line <m>y = -x + 2</m>. Use a dashed line since the inequality will not include equality.</li>
          <li>Test a point, like <m>(0,0)</m>. Substitute into <m>y \gt -x + 2</m>.</li>
          <li>Since <m>0 \gt -0 + 2</m> is false, shade the opposite side from <m>(0,0)</m>.</li>
          <li>Repeat the same process for <m>y \le 2x - 1</m>.</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Represent <m>y \gt x + 1</m> on a graph.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>Draw the line <m>y = x + 1</m> using a dashed line.</li>
            <li>Use a test point like <m>(0,0)</m>: <m>0 \gt 0 + 1</m> â†’ false.</li>
            <li>Shade the side that does <em>not</em> contain <m>(0,0)</m>.</li>
            <li>This shaded region shows all values that satisfy <m>y \gt x + 1</m>.</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise>
        <p><m>\textbf{Answer the following in your exercise book.}</m></p>
        <ol>
        <li>
            Draw a number line and graph the inequality <m>x \lt -1</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
            Represent <m>y \ge 2x - 3</m> on the Cartesian plane.
        </li>
        <li>
            Graph the inequality <m>y \lt -\frac{1}{2}x + 4</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
            Write two real-life examples that can be represented using inequalities.
        </li>
        <li>
            If <m>x \ge 2</m> and <m>x \lt 5</m>, shade the region on the number line that satisfies both.
        </li>
        </ol>
    </exercise>
  </subsubsection>
    <conclusion>
        <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway:}</m> Inequalities in two variables describe regions of the graph. Always draw the boundary line first, then use a test point to decide which side to shade. Use dashed or solid lines to indicate strict or inclusive inequalities.
        </p>
    </conclusion>
</subsection>